xxxii Introduction

The eastern fields, commonly known as the Barnwell Fielos, were four in number, and, counting from the south west, appear in the following order (see plan)¹:

1. Ford Field, so called from the ford by which the London Road entered the territory of Cambridge, lay

between the Trumpington Road and the Hills Road, but

was bounded on the townward side by what is now ’

Lensfield Road.

2. Middle Field lay between the Hills Road and the line of the Mill Road, but was bounded on the townward side by what is now Parker's Piece.

3. Bradmore or Bradmoor Field, called also Meledich, lay between the Mill Road and the Newmarket Road3 but the townward part of it was known as the Clayangles or Clayhanger.

4 Sturbridge Field, anciently called Estenhale‚ lay on both sides of the Newmarket Road just beyond Barnwell Priory.

Professor Maitland has obtained evidence which makes it clear that in Ford Field the site of Peterhouse and the tract subsequently called Swine Croft or St Thomas’ leys were once arable; that in Middle F ield, Parker’s Piece was arable; and that in Bradmoor Field, Christ's Piece also- was arable. The tract therefore which extended from Coe Fen to the Newmarket Road was in very ancient times one large cornfield. Subsequently part of these fields was laid down as grass, and then the word ‘ley' instead of the word ‘selion ¹ was used with reference to them. Some of the old selions may be detected to this day in the grounds of Downing College¹.

On the west side of Cambridge there were also four fietds, but, as our Memoranda do not busy themselves with them, 1 need not do more than mention them in a summary fashion.
